This paper deals with the computational complexity of a problem in the field of computational social choice, specifically the problem of indivisible goods exchange. This problem is a classic topic in the field of game theory and mechanism design, which falls under the category of cs.GT (Game Theory). The paper also uses techniques from parameterized complexity, which is a subfield of theoretical computer science that deals with the complexity of problems with natural parameters. Therefore, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is also a likely category. The paper also discusses the use of algorithms and computational techniques to solve the problem, which falls under the category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Additionally, the paper discusses the hardness of the problem, which is a topic in the field of computational complexity theory, falling under the category of cs.CC (Computational Complexity). Finally, the paper deals with the problem of exchange in economic settings, which is a topic in the field of computational economics, falling under the category of cs.EC (Computational Economics).
